            "answer_text": "About 100,000 British soldiers deserted during WW2. Why was this? One of my Father\u2019s friends was in Italy, after the end of World War II, at some huge US Army/Ally base. At this point, not only were there many troops from all sorts of different types of units, there were civilian employees, people being processed out, etc., so you\u2019d see all sorts of people on the base. The base had been transitioned without fighting between Italians, Germans, and Allies. One day, his company had a formation right before lunch and they confined everyone to their company area, this occurred across the post, civilian employers held their employees, the medical folks held mobile patients, the repo depot held their troops. Then the MP\u2019s, from different nations, including German authorities, Italian military and civilian police, investigators, and others swooped in on the mess halls and dining facilities and went through those there, those who\u2019d not been in actual units or actually employed. They found THOUSANDS OF DESERTERS, from every ally and axis force that had been in the area, unreturned, by choice, released detained Germans, Italian fascists, Italian partisans, Italian and other civilians, people who\u2019d drifted in from concentration camps to the North, what we\u2019d call illegal immigrants, DP\u2019s, displaced people, adventurers from Central America, and shit loads of on the run criminals from the allied forces, as well as simple deserters and those who didn\u2019t want to go home! Many of them were not only former enemies but friends and business associates, married to local women, coming in for free food! Deserters-you can have a soldier who gets drunk and wanders off into the woods and passes out and dies of hypothermia rather than comes back to the barracks and he\u2019s listed as a deserter. Same happens if a local kills him and the body isn\u2019t found, or he gets killed and dumped in a river on pay day by another soldier. During the chaos, a guy can get transferred and be listed as deserters. Then during crisis, you can have a pick up unit, some officer is going around grabbing every soldier he can to plug a gap and names aren\u2019t even being taken. Those men who stepped up during the German attack of the Battle of the Bulge might have run or might have been manning a Browning machinegun and got crushed beneath a tank\u2019s tracks, and if no one knows, it\u2019s assumed he\u2019s a deserter. With crap record keeping, paperwork lost or destroyed, more than a few soldiers have been startled to find they\u2019ve been listed as a deserter in an old unit. This is one of the many, many reasons soldiers in the US use to get MANY copies of orders, a set is intended for the old, losing unit. Every once in a while, a soldier, sailor, or airman is on liberty, a pass, or leave, or simply off duty and he vanishes, well, he\u2019s AWOL at first then a deserter after 30 days. ",
