            "answer_text": "Catch 22. Who, in their right mind wouldn\u2019t desert? 50,000 Americans over three years, 100,000 British, over five years . Some just buggered off! Spike Milligan was found, hiding and shivering in a fox hole. He had been a line layer, which put him at the front of the front line, spotting for the artillery. His books on the war are full of humour, but he spent years in ever present danger. Most of the soldiers had Fathers who had fought in WW1. They saw the hollow promise of \u2018A Land Fit For Heroes\u2019. Many had lived through the Depression and their views of what they were fighting for were influenced by the evidence of recent history. And now\u2026.. Through industry and enterprise, rather than by force of Arms, both Germany and Japan have the spheres of influence that they lost WW2 trying to obtain. That war was caused by arseholes who wanted to punish Germany for WWI. But we do not learn! Russia is in the same mental condition as Germany in the 1920s and 1930s. Sidelined derogated and simmering with anger. Russia does not have Jews to focus on, it has Gays. It has Islam. It has a former greatness to look back on. If Russia is a monster, then the West created it. So\u2026 After stacking up naked dead bodies in WW1, my Granddad could almost be forgiven for being cynical about the re-match. Mesopotamia. 1917. Rudyard Kipling. Mesopotamia BY RUDYARD KIPLING 1917 They shall not return to us, the resolute, the young, The eager and whole-hearted whom we gave: But the men who left them thriftily to die in their own dung, Shall they come with years and honour to the grave? They shall not return to us, the strong men coldly slain In sight of help denied from day to day: But the men who edged their agonies and chid them in their pain, Are they too strong and wise to put away? Our dead shall not return to us while Day and Night divide\u2014 Never while the bars of sunset hold. But the idle-minded overlings who quibbled while they died, Shall they thrust for high employments as of old? Shall we only threaten and be angry for an hour? When the storm is ended shall we find How softly but how swiftly they have sidled back to power By the favour and contrivance of their kind? Even while they soothe us, while they promise large amends, Even while they make a show of fear, Do they call upon their debtors, and take counsel with their friends, To conform and re-establish each career? Their lives cannot repay us\u2014their death could not undo\u2014 The shame that they have laid upon our race. But the slothfulness that wasted and the arrogance that slew, Shall we leave it unabated in its place? . ",
