            "answer_text": "About 100,000 British soldiers deserted during WW2. Why was this? I\u2019m confused as to the reason this question is raised anonymously. I assume it comes from the recent book release \u2018The Deserters\u2019, by journalist Charles Glass. He states that around 100,000 British, and 50,000 US troops deserted. If you read through some of the text, and some of the reviews, he tells you. \"In the American army, only about 10 percent of the soldiers in uniform actually saw combat,\" Glass tells Fresh Air's Dave Davies, \"and they were very rarely rotated out of the fronts. Most of the people [who] deserted were those who broke down in battle\u2026\u201d WWII 'Deserters': Stories Of Men Who Left The Front Lines \u201c\"Some units had much higher rates [of desertion] than others. The 36th in the battles in France had the highest rate of any division in the American Army. It can't be accidental that there were junior officers ... who were not interested in their men, and not talking to their men, and not looking after their men\u2026.\u201d Apparently, Germany executed 15,000 for desertion. I found this out in 5 minutes using a \u2018reputable search engine\u2019. If you need this for your homework, maybe put the same effort in. ",
